post_text:
Updated policy for Jamboree game at O'Neill on Tuesday, August 24th:
Volleyball Specific
• Teams will not switch benches between sets
• There will be a designated area in the bleachers for masks and no masks. Please sit in your preferred location, do not go to the other section, and maintain proper social distancing.
• Locker rooms will be disinfected prior to your arrival.
• Concessions will be provided
• Each team bench will have a marked off space that no fans will be allowed to be in.
• All elementary aged students are expected to sit with their parents/guardians. They will not be allowed to be in the hallways except when going to the restroom or concessions.
• No crock pots or meals will be allowed to be served to the players. They may have a grab and go type meal that they can eat on their bus.
• No fans will be allowed inside the basketball court following a game. We ask that everyone leave the facility as soon as the final game is done.
text:
Updated policy for Jamboree game at O'Neill on Tuesday, August 24th:
Volleyball Specific
• Teams will not switch benches between sets
• There will be a designated area in the bleachers for masks and no masks. Please sit in your preferred location, do not go to the other section, and maintain proper social distancing.
• Locker rooms will be disinfected prior to your arrival.
• Concessions will be provided
• Each team bench will have a marked off space that no fans will be allowed to be in.
• All elementary aged students are expected to sit with their parents/guardians. They will not be allowed to be in the hallways except when going to the restroom or concessions.
• No crock pots or meals will be allowed to be served to the players. They may have a grab and go type meal that they can eat on their bus.
• No fans will be allowed inside the basketball court following a game. We ask that everyone leave the facility as soon as the final game is done.

In the interest of science, Comet Neowise, the brightest comet in 23 years is now visible just after sunset in the northwest sky, to the right of where the sun sets. It will rise higher in the sky each day this week. It will be closest to Earth on July 22nd.

https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2020/07/13/comet-neowise-night-sky/
